overrides ARCWriterProcessor#writeHttp. Your\n&gt;&gt;version would ask the passed CrawlURI for its content type --\n&gt;&gt;CrawlURI#getContentType -- and then if not text/html, you&#39;d return\n&gt;&gt;otherwise call the parent&#39;s writeHttp implementation.\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;St.Ack\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;    \n&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;ansi\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;======= 2004-07-14 13:35:01 =======\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt; \n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;      \n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;It looks like the actual implementation of content negotiation with\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;the &#39;Accept:&#39; header does not work the way you think it does. I tried\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;with various servers (IIS, Apache, and GWS) and they all appear to\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;have the same behavior: if the content type of the requested resource\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;is a complete mismatch of the Accept: header, the resource is returned\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;anyway instead of returning a 406 as the HTTP/1.1 specification would\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;imply they should.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;That would explain why forcing &quot;Accept: text/html&quot; will still return\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;images with a 200 response.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;It could also be the case that the individual servers have content\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;negotiation turned off, or it is not fully implemented, or...\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;A quick scan of the Apache 2.0.50 content negotiation module would\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;imply that a 406 should be returned.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;FWIW, I added the &quot;accept-headers&quot; parameter to the HTML fetcher so I\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;could force the Accept-Language header --- I&#39;ve never used straight\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&quot;Accept:&quot;.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;  -tree\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;-- \n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Tom Emerson                                          Basis Technology Corp.\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Software Architect         